	doi = {10.5194/acp-21-18227-2021},
	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} Questions about how emissions are changing during the COVID-19 lockdown periods cannot be answered by observations of atmospheric trace gas concentrations alone, in part due to simultaneous changes in atmospheric transport, emissions, dynamics, photochemistry, and chemical feedback. A chemical transport model simulation benefiting from a multi-species inversion framework using well-characterized observations should differentiate those influences enabling to closely examine changes in emissions. Accordingly, we jointly constrain NO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{\textit{x}}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} and VOC emissions using well-characterized TROPOspheric Monitoring Instrument (TROPOMI) HCHO and NO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} columns during the months of March, April, and May 2020 (lockdown) and 2019 (baseline). We observe a noticeable decline in the magnitude of NO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{\textit{x}}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} emissions in March 2020 (14 \%–31 \%) in several major cities including Paris, London, Madrid, and Milan, expanding further to Rome, Brussels, Frankfurt, Warsaw, Belgrade, Kyiv, and Moscow (34 \%–51 \%) in April. However, NO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{\textit{x}}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} emissions remain at somewhat similar values or even higher in some portions of the UK, Poland, and Moscow in March 2020 compared to the baseline, possibly due to the timeline of restrictions. Comparisons against surface monitoring stations indicate that the constrained model underrepresents the reduction in surface NO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}. This underrepresentation correlates with the TROPOMI frequency impacted by cloudiness. During the month of April, when ample TROPOMI samples are present, the surface NO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} reductions occurring in polluted areas are described fairly well by the model (model: {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}−{\textless}/span{\textgreater}21 {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}±{\textless}/span{\textgreater} 17 \%, observation: {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}−{\textless}/span{\textgreater}29 {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}±{\textless}/span{\textgreater} 21 \%). The observational constraint on VOC emissions is found to be generally weak except for lower latitudes. Results support an increase in surface ozone during the lockdown. In April, the constrained model features a reasonable agreement with maximum daily 8 h average (MDA8) ozone changes observed at the surface ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{r}=0{\textless}/span{\textgreater}.43), specifically over central Europe where ozone enhancements prevail (model: {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}+{\textless}/span{\textgreater}3.73 {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}±{\textless}/span{\textgreater} 3.94 \%, {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}+{\textless}/span{\textgreater}1.79 ppbv, observation: {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}+{\textless}/span{\textgreater}7.35 {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}±{\textless}/span{\textgreater} 11.27 \%, {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}+{\textless}/span{\textgreater}3.76 ppbv). The model suggests that physical processes (dry deposition, advection, and diffusion) decrease MDA8 surface ozone in the same month on average by {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}−{\textless}/span{\textgreater}4.83 ppbv, while ozone production rates dampened by largely negative {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}{\textless}math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M19" display="inline" overflow="scroll" dspmath="mathml"{\textgreater}{\textless}mrow{\textgreater}{\textless}msub{\textgreater}{\textless}mi{\textgreater}J{\textless}/mi{\textgreater}{\textless}mrow class="chem"{\textgreater}{\textless}msub{\textgreater}{\textless}mi mathvariant="normal"{\textgreater}NO{\textless}/mi{\textgreater}{\textless}mn mathvariant="normal"{\textgreater}2{\textless}/mn{\textgreater}{\textless}/msub{\textgreater}{\textless}/mrow{\textgreater}{\textless}/msub{\textgreater}{\textless}/mrow{\textgreater}{\textless}/math{\textgreater}{\textless}span{\textgreater}{\textless}svg:svg xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="23pt" height="14pt" class="svg-formula" dspmath="mathimg" md5hash="fb225b36f4647bbe458cf3624847db35"{\textgreater}{\textless}svg:image xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="acp-21-18227-2021-ie00001.svg" width="23pt" height="14pt" src="acp-21-18227-2021-ie00001.png"/{\textgreater}{\textless}/svg:svg{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}[NO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}]-{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}{\textless}math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M21" display="inline" overflow="scroll" dspmath="mathml"{\textgreater}{\textless}mrow{\textgreater}{\textless}msub{\textgreater}{\textless}mi{\textgreater}k{\textless}/mi{\textgreater}{\textless}mrow class="chem"{\textgreater}{\textless}mi mathvariant="normal"{\textgreater}NO{\textless}/mi{\textgreater}{\textless}mo{\textgreater}+{\textless}/mo{\textgreater}{\textless}msub{\textgreater}{\textless}mi mathvariant="normal"{\textgreater}O{\textless}/mi{\textgreater}{\textless}mn mathvariant="normal"{\textgreater}3{\textless}/mn{\textgreater}{\textless}/msub{\textgreater}{\textless}/mrow{\textgreater}{\textless}/msub{\textgreater}{\textless}/mrow{\textgreater}{\textless}/math{\textgreater}{\textless}span{\textgreater}{\textless}svg:svg xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="35pt" height="14pt" class="svg-formula" dspmath="mathimg" md5hash="38f7581ee295132097e596660c88727c"{\textgreater}{\textless}svg:image xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="acp-21-18227-2021-ie00002.svg" width="35pt" height="14pt" src="acp-21-18227-2021-ie00002.png"/{\textgreater}{\textless}/svg:svg{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}[NO][O{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}] become less negative, leading ozone to increase by {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}+{\textless}/span{\textgreater}5.89 ppbv. Experiments involving fixed anthropogenic emissions suggest that meteorology contributes to 42 \% enhancement in MDA8 surface ozone over the same region with the remaining part (58 \%) coming from changes in anthropogenic emissions. Results illustrate the capability of satellite data of major ozone precursors to help atmospheric models capture ozone changes induced by abrupt emission anomalies.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
